Subject: categories: Re: Grothendieck toposes=0A=
=0A=
I would tend to assume that a "Grothendieck topos" is one bounded over=0A=
"Set", whatever the current meaning of "Set" is, and in particular=0A=
whether or not "Set" is classical.  Thus, when working in the internal=0A=
language of an arbitrary topos S, I would say "Grothendieck topos" to=0A=
mean what *externally* to S would be called a bounded S-topos.=0A=
=0A=
On Fri, Oct 28, 2016 at 12:08 PM, David Yetter <dyetter@ksu.edu> wrote:=0A=
> I, for one, would assume the same meaning for the phrase "Grothendieck to=
pos" as is used in the Elephant.=0A=
